      "original_coefficient_value_reference": 0.3907,
      "original_coefficient_value_reported": null,
      "original_cos_notes": "The model includes both crossed and nested effects, making the power analysis somewhat complicated. The variance due to province is very small, resulting in a small ICC and so the nested within province was ignored for this analysis as it will not really affect the final numbers. Items are nested within condition and condition is within-subjects, so the dfs of the comparison of interest is controlled mainly by the number of items, rather than the number of stimuli. The number of participants has a very small effect on power in this case. For this power analysis, I set the number of participants to a constant (500 in this case) to investigate an approximate number of stimuli that would be needed. I used the ‘Power ANalysis for GEneral Anova designs’ designed by Jake Westfall (<a href=\"https://jakewestfall.shinyapps.io/pangea/\" class=\"uri\">https://jakewestfall.shinyapps.io/pangea/</a>) and used the author provided output to calculate the needed parameter estimates [I used PANGEA, rather than one of his shiny apps for crossed random effects b/c of the need for custom contrats]. Because I ignored some small aspects of the design (e.g. province, random effect for age), the ncp (i.e. t-value) estimated by the shiny app for original inputs is lower than the actual reported t-value, which means that the required number of stimuli is conservative. In truth, less than the required N of stimuli would actually be needed, but the general pattern would hold that the number of stimuli has a far greater effect on power than the number of participants, and holding the number of stimuli constant while changing the number of participants will never reach adequate power for SCORE with the original design. Images of the inputs & outputs are provided in the OSF power component.",
